# Staylight — Architecture

## Stack

Next.js App Router · TypeScript · Tailwind CSS

## Directory Layout

| Path | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `app/` | Pages, layouts, route segments (App Router) |
| `app/api/` | API route handlers (backend) |
| `lib/data/` | Seeded mock data (JSON/TS modules) |
| `lib/services/` | Business logic (stays, bookings, reviews, search) |
| `lib/smart-match/` | Smart Match scoring engine |
| `types/` | Shared TypeScript types/interfaces |
| `components/` | Reusable UI components |

## Layering Rules

- **API routes** validate input, call services, return JSON — keep handlers thin
- **Services** own business logic; never import React or UI code
- **Smart Match** is pure rule-based logic; consumed by search/listing services
- **Components** fetch via API routes or receive server-fetched props — no direct seed imports in client components
- **Types** are the single source of truth for domain models (`Stay`, `Booking`, `Review`, `SearchParams`, etc.)

## API Conventions

- REST-style routes under `app/api/` (e.g. `stays`, `stays/[id]`, `bookings`, `reviews`)
- Return consistent error shapes: `{ error: string }` with appropriate HTTP status
- Log requests/responses at info level; log errors with context (route, params, message)

## Principles

- **Do not over-engineer** — no repository pattern, no DI framework, no ORM
- Prefer plain functions and modules over classes
- Colocate route-specific UI in `app/`; extract only when reused
- Use Next.js server components where data fetching is straightforward; client components for interactivity

## Testing

- Unit tests for Smart Match and key service functions
- One or two integration/smoke tests for critical API routes
- Keep test setup minimal (Vitest or Jest — match scaffold choice)
